Data¶

Personal Data¶

  • age (numeric)
  • job : type of job (categorical)
  • marital : marital status (categorical)
  • education (categorical)
  • default: has credit in default? (binary)
  • balance: average yearly balance, in euros (numeric)
  • housing: has housing loan? (binary)
  • loan: has personal loan? (binary)

Last Contact¶

Related with the last contact of the current campaign:

  • contact: contact communication type (categorical)
  • day: last contact day of the month (numeric)
  • month: last contact month of year (categorical)
  • duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric)

Campaign¶

Other attributes:

  • campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)
  • pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric)
    • -1 means client was not previously contacted)
  • previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)
  • poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical)

Output variable (desired target): 17 - y - has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: "yes","no")

  • Preprocessing Pipeline
    • Start simple
    • Incrementally add features to pipeline

    • Boosting

Criteria¶

  • Works with Pandas (small - medium sized tasks)
  • Works with SKLearn Estimators
  • Can handle workflow -- Train, Test, Production
  • Extensible -- Easy to extend for custom needs
  • Compatible -- Can reuse specialized libraries

Transformations¶

  • Missing
    • Continuous - Median
    • Categorical - Most Frequent
    • Present Column
  • Binning
    • Age
  • One Hot Encoding
    • Job
    • Eduation
    • Default
    • Housing
    • Loan
    • Contact
    • Poutcome
    • Age Bin (Chained to Binning)
  • Label / Ordinal Encoding
    • Day
    • Month
  • Standardize / Normalize
    • Balance
    • Duration
    • Campaign
    • Previous
  • Custom Logic
    • Pdays

Standardize¶

  • We need to scale our training data, and apply the transformation to the test data
  • Standardization - subtract mean and divide by std deviation
In [158]:
def standardize(train, test):
    mean = train.mean()
    std = train.std() 
    train = (train - mean) / std
    test  = (test - mean)  / std
    return (train, test, mean, std)
In [159]:
cols = ['balance', 'previous', 'duration', 'campaign']
for col in cols:
    train, test, _, _ = standardize(X_train[col], X_test[col])
    X_train[col] = train
    X_test[col]  = test

Impute Median¶

  • Impute after standardizing
In [160]:
def imputeMedian(train, test, col):
    med = train[col].median()
    train[col].fillna(med)
    test[col].fillna(med)
    return med
In [161]:
cols = ['balance', 'previous', 'duration', 'campaign']
for col in cols:
    imputeMedian(X_train, X_test, col)

Pipeline¶

In [194]:
numFeatures    = ['balance', 'previous', 'duration', 'campaign']
numTransformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('scaler',  StandardScaler()),
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median'))
])

oheFeatures    = ['job', 'marital', 'education', 'default', 'housing', 'loan', 'contact', 'poutcome', 'age_bin']
oheTransformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('ohe', OneHotEncoder())
])

ordFeatures    = ['month', 'day']
ordTransformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('le', OrdinalEncoder())
])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(transformers=[
    ('num', numTransformer, numFeatures),
    ('ohe', oheTransformer, oheFeatures),
    ('le',  ordTransformer,  ordFeatures)
])

rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=50)
clf = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                      ('classifier',   rf)])

DataFrameMapper¶

  • Billed as aproviding a bridge between Sklearn's ML methods and Pandas DataFrames
  • Provides a means to map DataFrame columns to transformations
  • Adds transformers for working with Pandas
    • CategoricalImputer
    • FunctionTransformer

Discussion¶

  • Good complement, can use SKLearn preprocessing and get data frames out
  • Thought & Implementation given to cardinality of transforms and columns
  • Starters for functional transformations and category imputation
  • Excludes columns not mapped - you need to add a None transformer

PDPipe¶

  • Provides an opinionated and concise interface for building Pandas pipelines that have
    • Preconditions
    • Support fit-transform design of sklearn
    • Serializable
    • Informative prints and errors
  • Simple pipeline arithmetic

Pipeline¶

In [63]:
numFeatures    = ['balance', 'previous', 'duration', 'campaign']
oheFeatures    = ['job', 'marital', 'education', 'default', 'housing', 'loan', 'contact', 'poutcome', 'age_bin']
ordFeatures    = ['month', 'day']
In [64]:
pipe     = pdp.ColByFrameFunc('pdays_present', lambda df: np.where(df.pdays == -1, 0, 1))
pipe    += pdp.Bin({'age': [0,30,40,50,60,100]})
pipe    += pdp.ColRename({'age': 'age_bin'}) 
pipe    += pdp.OneHotEncode(columns=oheFeatures, drop_first=False)
pipe    += pdp.Encode(columns=ordFeatures)
pipe    += pdp.Scale('StandardScaler')

Discussion¶

  • From a code perspective PDPipe was the most elegant
    • Simple Interface to Transforms
    • Fluid coding made easy += operator for assembling stages
    • Succinct - not a lot of lines of code, and easy to grok
    • Fit / Transform
  • Production - comparable to sklearn Pipeline
  • Classifier not grouped into pipeline (Not a big pain point for me)
  • Beta (nicely documented but lacking implementation in areas)
    • Lacks SimpleImputer
    • Scaler applies to all columns
  • Felt sluggish on transform method for some reason
  • Extensible in terms of number of stages
    • Inheriting PdPipelineStage
    • Alternatively, use AdhocPipeline & pass transform function in constructor
